title: Avian
write_up: The lyrics encapstulate the (drug-related) feeling of wanting to escape our bodies: There's a bird in the sky / Look at him fly / Why, why, why, why, why

title: Skyfall (ft. Young Thug)
write_up: Travis Scott comes close to Young Thug's planet, a credit to him, considering it's his song

title: Nike Just Do It
write_up: (Come be an absent person with me, this is my world, and it's amazing)

title: Self Control
write_up: Featuring a Yung Lean bridge, Self Control is where Blonde finds itself approaching pop stardom, Frank Ocean bending his voice in and out of a wavering guitar, exploring the edges of how we come to understand ourselves, while never abandoing its mass appeal

title: Lil Haiti Baby
write_up: Shoot in broad day, shoot in broad day

title: Smoke Again (ft. Ab-Soul)
write_up: Before he lost his abilility to control how people thought of him, Chance the Rapper had his reputation for a reason. His music is  silliy and earnest, but it has a unmistakable real youthful driving energy

title: Brand New
write_up: The second half of the 2010s found rappers entering waves of internet cloud rap clout that vanished as soon as they lost their edge (loosely defined as the marriage between esoteric beat selection and novel melodic sensibility For a year or two, Yung Bans had it in spades.

title: All Day
write_up: (life is great and I'm happy to be alive)

title: Hannah Montana
write_up: Brute force leaves us with nothing to do but react. Cocaine, cocaine, cocaine, with energy and enthusiasim. They didn't particualrly evolve into saying anything different, but they were often able to recreate this initial burst of energy, not only on a local Atlanta scale but on a national and eventually international scale.

title: Florida
write_up: Accesible indie-pop that traces over moods quite easily and without every staying too long within its own sentimality. Able to construct something of a world through old-style M83 synths.

title: Look At Me!
write_up: It's hard to shock teenagers. XXXtentacion did it here. For a month or two this song was all people talked about, its crude sexuality doubling as both an emotional gateway and as a full-fledged emphasis on why you should stay the fuck away from him

title: Lance Jr.
write_up: Jacking off to fall asleep

title: Ashley Olsen
write_up: Their lyrical back and forth culminates with the great reprise on the choruses

title: Yah Mean
write_up: Almost as if Playboi Carti was never meant to do anything but build emotional soundscapes meant for people who like to feel when they listen to music. The lyrics here, are nothing compared to his ability to layer his vocal intonations over top of each other in the blank spaces of dreamy cloud rap

title: Uncast Shadow of a Southern Myth
Peach Boy
write_up: Jay Som is another piece of evidence for queer women's indie rock takeover.

title: Devon
write_up: Grimes is the cosmic stadium constructer of the decade, and Devon explores an inner world so unique and personal that it's impossible to emotionally articulate. I want someone to make a song about me like this.

title: Hallucinating
write_up: Classic future song, nothing revolutionary in terms of his catalogue, but for any other rapper it would be their greatest song

title: Harps
write_up: While their most important music is in their first three projects, the Sea and Cake are one of the most consistently creative indie bands for a reason. Harps glides across the sky.

title: Neighborhood Hero
write_up: Bleakness is standard for drill, but Lil Durk finds his own melodic corner of it. Great lines.

title: It's Real
write_up: While a step below their more creative self-titled release, it's refined processed slow-paced indie rock that has its heart in the right place.

title: Tity and Dolla (ft. Hugh Augustine and Jay Rock)
write_up: "Mom's said I lost the plot at least I never lost my crop"

title: Headlines
write_up: His popular music omnipresence is hard to take, but his natural stage presence still comes through like a truck. Classic hook.

title: Set Dat Bitch Off (Remix)
write_up: This DC-based, A$AP Mob affialiate never really found his place in the popular rap conversation, though with ICYTWAT's help, here he finds himself navigating being the center of an never ending underground rave as if he'd been there his whole life

title: SMUCKERS (ft. Kanye West and Lil Wayne)
I Bet On Losing Dogs
write_up: (I can't stop ruining my life). Self-destruction is most likely the easiest topic for depressive, lonely, music listeners to connect with.

title: Buss It
write_up: "She say she love me"

title: No
write_up: The lines here, though in Spanish, are wonderfully poetic. No hay que ver el futuro / Para saber lo que va a pasar. (You don't have to see the future to know what's going to happen).

title: Dad
write_up: Takes the emotional ethos of cloud rap and purifies it into a unique vision, accompanied by wonderful production that understands itself perfectly

title: Souljahwitch's Faith
write_up: Lil Tracy filtered his weed addiction/depression into pure agnst, also showing his rare lyrical side

title: Baby What's Wrong With You
write_up: A great song that might be his most outwardly influential. Pretty much establishes: This is what you can do with cloud rap. Have fun.

title: Depreston
write_up: Courtney Barnett has a genius conversational style, here it slows down into world building. It casually takes the engaged listener around a house, and she complains about the world in ways that bother you too. Courtney Barnett understands her voice a lot more than a lot of more naturally dynamic singers do.

title: 1539 N. Calvert
write_up: Classic line after classice line. Long extended intro before launching into the most ridicously catchy flow you've ever heard

title: Yeah Yeah
write_up: Longest Hook ever.

title: Super Rich Kids (ft. Earl Sweatshirt)
write_up: While Frank Ocean traces over the many problems that affluent kids can have, Earl Sweartshirt applies his own childhood to a show-stopping verse

title: 2 Cups Stuffed
write_up: (Lean, lean, lean lean lean), (500 DNA in my ding-ding), (L-E-A-N-I-N-G), relentess energy

title: Feelin' the Love
write_up: I hear the synths from this song when I wake up in the morning, after not listening to this song for a year or two. Instantly memorable.

title: Bleach
write_up: Cloud Rap has arrived

title: Fall Off
write_up: His signature: making one line, even one word, into a mountain of feeling

title: Purple Reign
write_up: (Why can't I be happy)

title: I'll Tell You What
write_up: Out of all of Young Thug's most quotable songs, this is at the top. Non-sequitors that really aren't non-sequitors as much as catcchiness inseperapably piled up on top of itself, strange and understated production, trap music at its most unavoidable

title: M.A.A.D City
write_up: YAK YAK YAK. Kendrick Lamar is rightfully acknoweldged as rap's greatest lyricist of the decade, but here he is somehow able to find pop stardom in the form of a violent relentlessness basking in the urban sprawl of Los Angeles

title: White Tee
write_up: Lil Tracy and Lil Peep were the greatest rap duo of the decade, besides, I guess, Young Thug and Rich Homie Quan, but even then their interplay has nothing on Lil Tracy/Lil Peep who exchange between themselves so effortlessly it's as if they were the same person

title: Woah Woah Woah (ft. Bali Baby)
write_up: Somewhere along the way, Trippie Redd became confused, and it's too bad he did, because if he didn't, we would have had albums full of emotional highs that enter your headspace so conclusively it's hard to imagine of anything except his world

title: Rawlings
write_up: Keef's most pure example of his savant-like sensibility for intros, Rawlings finds his wonderful chemistry with DP Beats reaching into the depths of your heart to pull out what's left of it, its synths excavators, his gritty voice the moon shining its light on you from up above the hole.

title: Devil in a New Dress (ft. Rick Ross)
SomebodyPlease/Armour/Hunger
write_up: SomebodyPlease/Amour/Hunger combines the gritty NY production of its album with some of MIKE's most emotionally direct ramblings in one of the best album openers of the decade. Hard to find an album that fits into its environment better than this one.

title: No Shoes On The Rug, Leave Them At The Door
write_up: (It is difficult for me to reach my mom's expectations of me, and it makes me feel bad about myself)

title: Citgo
write_up: Lauded generally online as the 'start' of what melodic rap could do, Citgo is still as powerful as it likely was (I was listening to the arctic monkeys back then instead) the day it came out. Citgo is one of the premier landmarks for cloud rap.  Chief Keef is a visionary artist who deserves to be listed in the same breath of the Built to Spill, Kurosawa, and Gabriel Garcia Marquez

title: Like Dat
write_up: I know every line of this song by heart, ten times over. Kodak Black was born to rap.

title: Throw Away
write_up: (I fucked up. I know I did, but I still have feelings for you so can you forgive me. I love you.)

title: Came Out Of a Lady
write_up: ( Iam unabashedly in love, the kind of love that can bring me out of pain and into the world of self-certainty, a love that makes the rest of the world finally bearable. I just can't believe it.)

title: Grab The Wheel
write_up: "When I'm in DC they call me Moe". Before I got into Young Thug, Uzi was both the warmth of my hometown and the love of human  feeling. Uzi will always have an almost unberable talent for unique song construction, with melodies effortlessly cascading over each other, and here it comes about as close as you can to perfection. The synths near the end are brilliant.
